2095: Delete the Middle Node of a Linked List
Problem Statement

Given the head of a singly linked list, delete the middle node and return the head of the modified linked list.

For an odd-length list, the middle node is the exact center.
For an even-length list, the second middle node is considered the middle.
Examples
Input:  1 -> 3 -> 4 -> 7 -> 1 -> 2 -> 6
Output: 1 -> 3 -> 4 -> 1 -> 2 -> 6
Input:  1 -> 2 -> 3 -> 4
Output: 1 -> 2 -> 4
Intuition

To delete the middle node efficiently:

Use Slow and Fast Pointers to find the middle node.
Maintain a prev pointer to track the node before the middle.
Once the middle node is found, skip it by updating the next pointer of prev.

This avoids calculating the length of the linked list separately.

Approach
Step 1: Handle Edge Case

If the list contains only one node, deleting the middle node results in an empty list.

if (head == null || head.next == null) {
    return null;
}
Step 2: Initialize Pointers
ListNode slow = head;
ListNode fast = head;
ListNode prev = null;
slow moves one step at a time.
fast moves two steps at a time.
prev stores the node before slow.
Step 3: Find the Middle Node
while (fast != null && fast.next != null) {
    prev = slow;
    slow = slow.next;
    fast = fast.next.next;
}

When the loop ends:

slow points to the middle node.
prev points to the node just before the middle.
Step 4: Delete the Middle Node
prev.next = slow.next;

This bypasses the middle node and removes it from the linked list.

Step 5: Return the Head
return head;
Code
class Solution {
    public ListNode deleteMiddle(ListNode head) {

        if (head == null || head.next == null) {
            return null;
        }

        ListNode slow = head;
        ListNode fast = head;
        ListNode prev = null;

        while (fast != null && fast.next != null) {
            prev = slow;
            slow = slow.next;
            fast = fast.next.next;
        }

        prev.next = slow.next;

        return head;
    }
}
Dry Run
Input
1 -> 2 -> 3 -> 4 -> 5
Initial State
prev = null
slow = 1
fast = 1
Iteration 1
prev = 1
slow = 2
fast = 3
Iteration 2
prev = 2
slow = 3
fast = 5

Loop ends.

prev = 2
slow = 3 (middle node)

Delete middle:

2 -> 3 -> 4

becomes

2 -----> 4

Result:

1 -> 2 -> 4 -> 5
Complexity Analysis
Time Complexity
O(n)

The linked list is traversed only once.

Space Complexity
O(1)

Only a few pointers are used.

Key Concepts Learned
Slow & Fast Pointer Technique
slow = slow.next;
fast = fast.next.next;

Used to find the middle node efficiently.

Node Deletion
prev.next = slow.next;

Removes a node by bypassing it.

Pattern Learned

Find Middle + Delete Node

Find the middle node using slow and fast pointers.
Keep track of the previous node.
Skip the middle node using pointer manipulation.

This pattern is commonly used in linked list problems involving:

Finding the middle node
Deleting specific nodes
Fast and slow pointer traversal
Takeaway

The optimal solution uses the Slow & Fast Pointer technique to locate the middle node in a single traversal and deletes it using pointer manipulation.

